<body>
<p>
The map \(T\in\End(V)\) induces a linear map
\[\Lambda^nT\in\End(\Alt^n(V))\qquad\text{given by}\qquad
v_1\wedge\dots\wedge v_n\mapsto Tv_1\wedge\dots\wedge Tv_n.\]
Here, \(\Alt^n(V)\) is the \(n\)th
<a knowl="defs/vec/alt-alg">alternating power</a>.
</p>
<p>
Since \(\Alt^n(V)\) is 1 dimensional, this map must be
multiplication by some scalar, i.e. we have
\[\Lambda^nT(v_1\wedge\dots\wedge v_n) = D(v_1\wedge\dots\wedge v_n)\]
for some \(D\in\mathbf F\). We define the <b>determinant</b> of \(T\)
(denoted \(\det T\)) to be this scalar \(D\).
</p>
<p>
Related: <a knowl="facts/vec/det">facts about the determinant</a>.
</p>
</body>
</html>
